  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Should kids take immune gummies year-round or just during cold season?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'For maximum benefit, immune gummies should be taken year-round rather than only during cold and flu season. The Cochrane vitamin C review specifically found that benefits came from consistent daily supplementation, not from starting supplementation after symptoms appeared. Vitamin D levels take 2-3 months to optimize, making year-round supplementation important, especially in northern latitudes where winter sun exposure is insufficient. Zinc stores must be maintained consistently. Starting immune supplements only when a child gets sick provides minimal benefit — the protective effects come from sustained, daily supplementation.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Can kids take too many immune gummies?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Yes, excessive intake of immune gummies can cause adverse effects. Too much vitamin C (above the tolerable upper limit of 400mg for ages 1-3, 650mg for ages 4-8) can cause diarrhea and stomach upset. Excessive zinc (above 7mg for ages 1-3, 12mg for ages 4-8) can cause nausea, vomiting, and copper deficiency over time. Too much vitamin D (above 2,500 IU for ages 1-3, 3,000 IU for ages 4-8) can cause hypercalcemia. Ensure your child is not taking multiple supplements containing the same nutrients. Store gummies out of children\'s reach — their candy-like taste makes overconsumption a real risk.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Are elderberry gummies safe for kids?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Commercially prepared elderberry gummies made from cooked, processed elderberry extract are generally considered safe for children ages 2 and older. Raw or uncooked elderberries contain cyanogenic glycosides that can cause nausea and vomiting — commercial processing eliminates these compounds. A 2016 review in Phytochemistry Reviews concluded that processed elderberry supplements are safe for both children and adults. Some pediatric allergists note that elderberry may theoretically stimulate the immune system in ways that could be problematic for children with autoimmune conditions, though this has not been demonstrated in clinical studies.' } },
