    <h2 id="kids-immune-system">Why Children's Immune Systems Need Nutritional Support</h2>

    <p>Children's immune systems are still developing — they do not reach adult-level maturity until approximately age 7 to 8 for innate immunity and the teenage years for adaptive immunity. During this developmental window, school-age children average 6 to 8 upper respiratory infections per year, compared to 2 to 4 for adults. Each illness represents the immune system encountering a new pathogen and building a response, which is a normal part of immune education — but nutritional support can reduce the severity and duration of these inevitable infections.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">6-8</span>
