    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Immune Gummies for Kids</h2>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What are the most important immune nutrients for kids?</summary><p>Vitamin C (immune cell function), zinc (immune development), and vitamin D3 (immune gene regulation) are the three most evidence-based nutrients. Elderberry provides additional antiviral support.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Do immune gummies help kids get sick less?</summary><p>Regular vitamin C reduced cold duration by 14% in children (Cochrane). Zinc reduced cold duration by 1-2 days. Vitamin D reduced respiratory infections by 20% in deficient children. Results depend on baseline nutritional status.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>At what age can kids start immune gummies?</summary><p>Most brands recommend age 4+. Zarbee's and L'il Critters offer age 2+ options. Under 2: use liquid drops. Always supervise young children with gummy supplements.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Year-round or just cold season?</summary><p>Year-round provides maximum benefit. The Cochrane vitamin C review found benefits came from consistent daily supplementation, not from starting after illness onset. Vitamin D takes 2-3 months to optimize.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can kids take too many immune gummies?</summary><p>Yes. Excessive vitamin C causes diarrhea. Too much zinc causes nausea and copper deficiency. Excess vitamin D causes hypercalcemia. Check that multiple supplements don't overlap. Store out of children's reach.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Are elderberry gummies safe for kids?</summary><p>Processed elderberry extract gummies are safe for ages 2+. Raw elderberries contain harmful compounds removed during commercial processing. Avoid in children with autoimmune conditions without medical guidance.</p></details>

